          "body": "The chapter's closing verses (7:25-26) reveal an aspect of idolatry that contemporary readers consistently underestimate: its economic attractiveness. The Israelite soldier who defeats a Canaanite warrior sees an idol overlaid with gold and silver. The military victory is complete; the cult object is theologically disqualified; but it gleams. Moses's command is specific: 'You shall not covet the silver or the gold that is on them, nor take it for yourselves, or you will be snared by it' (7:25). The image-object is an abomination, but its economic value is real. The gold does not become neutral when it is detached from the idol; it remains contaminated by its association with what Yahweh calls detestable. Bringing it into the house places the household under the herem — the same category of destruction that applied to the original object (7:26). This is Deuteronomy's early warning of what Achan will demonstrate catastrophically in Joshua 7: the economic face of idolatry is the face most likely to find a welcome indoors. The chapter closes where it opened — with the herem — insisting that holiness admits no partial compliance."
